description.value: Terracotta 'kantharos' with scenes of the god Bes: the vessel has lost its foot, and the rim may be a clever restoration, or perhaps ancient and repaired. The fabric is a light brown clay, possibly a Nile silt, but maybe mixed with marl. This relief-ware vessel was made in two halves, but from slightly different moulds. On each side three acanthus leaves rise from the base with rosette-headed flowers emerging from them. To conceal the join between the two halves, a large acanthus-like leaf covers the side. The upper part of the scene is decorated with hanging garlands from which ribbons fall, and between them a figure of Bes dancing. He is semi-naked, with only a himation draped around his hips, one leg and arm raised. On his head he wears a three-feathered crown.
